@justinmc you can solve this problem much more simply, without using the `LayoutBuilder`.

The issue is actually the `OverlayEntry`, which will size its child to occupy as much space as possible. You can use the existing fieldKey to get the RenderBox of the text field and use that to size the options list widget. You'll need to introduce a container between the OverlayEntry and the options list to change the sizing constraints.

That way you don't need the postframe callback, which should simplify the tests

I was just walking through this error with @LongCatIsLooong and wanted to post a summary of why it happens. Run the repro code and select an option, and this is the process of the bug happening:

 [1.](https://github.com/flutter/flutter/blob/4d1161b5912b200d3e57dbd7c4161b2a6b321d7b/packages/flutter/lib/src/widgets/autocomplete.dart#L386) RawAutocomplete updates the field's TextEditingController to the selected string.

 [2.](https://github.com/flutter/flutter/blob/4d1161b5912b200d3e57dbd7c4161b2a6b321d7b/packages/flutter/lib/src/material/text_form_field.dart#L397) TextFormField, which has a listener on the disposed controller, schedules itself to rebuild.


 [3.](https://github.com/flutter/flutter/blob/4d1161b5912b200d3e57dbd7c4161b2a6b321d7b/packages/flutter/lib/src/widgets/autocomplete.dart#L390) RawAutocomplete calls onSelected, which calls the repro code and disposes the controller:

```dart
setState(() {
  controller.dispose();
  controller = TextEditingController(text: 'Last text');
});
```

 [4.](https://github.com/flutter/flutter/blob/4d1161b5912b200d3e57dbd7c4161b2a6b321d7b/packages/flutter/lib/src/material/text_field.dart#L1535) TextFormField rebuilds along with its underlying TextField, which ends up trying to add a listener on the disposed controller, which is what ultimately triggers the error in the stack trace.

Here is a repro case that has nothing to do with Autocomplete, to get to the root of the bug. I'm not sure if there is a bug that should be fixed here, or if Autocomplete should just work around it.

<details>

<summary>Repro code without Autocomplete</summary>

```dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';

void main() {
  runApp(const MyApp());
}

class MyApp extends StatelessWidget {
  const MyApp({super.key});

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return MaterialApp(
      title: 'Flutter Demo',
      theme: ThemeData(
        primarySwatch: Colors.blue,
      ),
      home: const MyHomePage(title: 'Flutter Demo Home Page'),
    );
  }
}

class MyHomePage extends StatelessWidget {
  const MyHomePage({super.key, required this.title});

  final String title;

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(
        title: Text(title),
      ),
      body: Center(
        child: Column(
          mainAxisAlignment: MainAxisAlignment.center,
          children: <Widget>[
            MyParentWidget(),
          ],
        ),
      ),
    );
  }
}

class MyParentWidget extends StatelessWidget {
  MyParentWidget({
    super.key,
  });

  final ValueNotifier<String> notifier = ValueNotifier<String>('one');

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Column(
      children: <Widget>[
        MyChildWidget(notifier: notifier),
        TextButton(
          onPressed: () {
            // When the value is changed, MyChildWidget is going to schedule a
            // build.
            notifier.value = 'two';
            // But then the notifier is disposed, so when MyChildWidget builds,
            // it will be building with a disposed notifier.
            notifier.dispose();
          },
          child: const Text('Click to cause bug'),
        ),
      ],
    );
  }
}

class MyChildWidget extends StatefulWidget {
  const MyChildWidget ({
    super.key,
    required this.notifier,
  });

  final ValueNotifier<String> notifier;

  @override
  State<MyChildWidget> createState() => _MyChildWidgetState();
}

class _MyChildWidgetState extends State<MyChildWidget> {
  int _numberOfTimesNotifierHasNotified = 0;

  @override
  void initState() {
    super.initState();

    widget.notifier.addListener(_handleNotifierChange);
  }

  @override
  void didUpdateWidget(MyChildWidget oldWidget) {
    super.didUpdateWidget(oldWidget);
    if (widget.notifier != oldWidget.notifier) {
      oldWidget.notifier.removeListener(_handleNotifierChange);
      widget.notifier.addListener(_handleNotifierChange);
    }
  }

  @override
  void dispose() {
    widget.notifier.removeListener(_handleNotifierChange);
    super.dispose();
  }

  _handleNotifierChange() {
    setState(() {
      _numberOfTimesNotifierHasNotified += 1;
    });
  }

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return AnimatedBuilder(
      // Listenable.merge will add a listener to widget.notifier, which is not
      // allowed on a disposed ValueNotifier.
      animation: Listenable.merge(<Listenable>[ widget.notifier ]),
      builder: (BuildContext context, Widget? child) {
        return Text('notifier is: ${widget.notifier.value} and has notified this many times: $_numberOfTimesNotifierHasNotified');
      },
    );
  }
}
```

</details>

> These are my findings from investigating the customer testing failures.
> 
> * When the tests run, the options view opens upwards, showing the right options.
> * When any option is tapped, a warning that the widget at that offset cannot be hit-tested is thrown.
> * Changing the underlying `RawAutocomplete`'s `optionsViewOpenDirection` to `.down` instead of the current `.up` makes it so that the options view opens downwards instead of upwards, but no warning is thrown and the tests all pass.


I can also reproduce this in the RawAutocomplete tests. Take the test `tapping on an option selects it` in `RawAutocomplete`, wrap the RawAutocomplete in a Center, and change its optionsViewOpenDirection to .up, and the test fails even though there is as much space above the field as below.

<details>
<summary>Sample code</summary>

```dart

import 'package:flutter/material.dart';
import 'package:flutter_test/flutter_test.dart';

void main() {
  const List<String> kOptions = <String>[
    'aardvark',
    'bobcat',
    'chameleon',
    'dingo',
    'elephant',
    'flamingo',
    'goose',
    'hippopotamus',
    'iguana',
    'jaguar',
    'koala',
    'lemur',
    'mouse',
    'northern white rhinoceros',
  ];

  testWidgets('tapping on an option selects it', (WidgetTester tester) async {
    final GlobalKey fieldKey = GlobalKey();
    final GlobalKey optionsKey = GlobalKey();
    late Iterable<String> lastOptions;
    late FocusNode focusNode;
    late TextEditingController textEditingController;

    await tester.pumpWidget(
      MaterialApp(
        home: Scaffold(
          body: Column(
            children: [
              Container(height: 100),
              RawAutocomplete<String>(
                optionsViewOpenDirection: OptionsViewOpenDirection.up,
                optionsBuilder: (TextEditingValue textEditingValue) {
                  return kOptions.where((String option) {
                    return option.contains(textEditingValue.text.toLowerCase());
                  });
                },
                fieldViewBuilder: (BuildContext context, TextEditingController fieldTextEditingController, FocusNode fieldFocusNode, VoidCallback onFieldSubmitted) {
                  focusNode = fieldFocusNode;
                  textEditingController = fieldTextEditingController;
                  return TextField(
                    key: fieldKey,
                    focusNode: focusNode,
                    controller: textEditingController,
                  );
                },
                optionsViewBuilder: (BuildContext context, AutocompleteOnSelected<String> onSelected, Iterable<String> options) {
                  lastOptions = options;
                  return Material(
                    elevation: 4.0,
                    child: ListView.builder(
                      key: optionsKey,
                      padding: const EdgeInsets.all(8.0),
                      itemCount: options.length,
                      itemBuilder: (BuildContext context, int index) {
                        final String option = options.elementAt(index);
                        return GestureDetector(
                          onTap: () {
                            onSelected(option);
                          },
                          child: ListTile(
                            title: Text(option),
                          ),
                        );
                      },
                    ),
                  );
                },
              ),
            ],
          ),
        ),
      ),
    );

    // The field is always rendered, but the options are not unless needed.
    expect(find.byKey(fieldKey), findsOneWidget);
    expect(find.byKey(optionsKey), findsNothing);

    // Tap on the text field to open the options.
    await tester.tap(find.byKey(fieldKey));
    await tester.pump();
    expect(find.byKey(optionsKey), findsOneWidget);
    expect(lastOptions.length, kOptions.length);

    await tester.tap(find.text(kOptions[2]));
    await tester.pump();

    expect(find.byKey(optionsKey), findsNothing);

    expect(textEditingController.text, equals(kOptions[2]));
  });
}
```

</details>
